re has been done already, thereby bootstrapping this into all of the common OS's.%0a%3c %0a%3c All nodes shall be running OLSR on the Wireless backbone interfaces.%0a%3c %0a%3c !Addressing%0a%3c Until such a time as zeroconf for the interfaces has been done, the address for the backbone interface should be in the 10.0.0.0/8 network.  This allows us to make every octet available for hosts, more or less ensuring we have ample supply of addresses to cover Buffalo, and much later, WNY.%0a%3c %0a%3c Client-facing interfaces (Such as the gateway address for client APs) should be any private segment, not in the 10.0.0.0/8 network (ie, 172.16.0.0/12 or 192.168.0.0/16).  Addresses ranges in this respect are up to the node operator to manage, and outside of the scope of this document.%0a%3c %0a%3c Your backbone interface, while you are free to explore the network, and find an open address, should not conflict with any other device.  IP's are first-come-first serve, so if there is another node at that address, you must move.%0a%3c %0a%3c The network coordinator should be approached for an address, as this person is able to quickly determine what nodes connected to BuffaloMesh.Net have taken which address.%0a%3c %0a%3c !Network coordinator%0a%3c The network coordinator shall be named as soon as feasible, and the goal is to have as-required elections to vote in the best coordinator for the time.%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
